    "origin_context": "LeT emerged from the geopolitics of the Soviet-Afghan War (1979-1989) and the subsequent struggle for Kashmir (1989-ongoing). Hafiz Saeed, an engineering professor and religious activist in the Ahl-e-Hadith (Salafi) school, founded Markaz-ud-Dawa-wal-Irshad (MDI) in 1985-1986 as a religious missionary organization with initial support from Saudi Arabia and Pakistan's ISI. As Soviet forces withdrew from Afghanistan, Pakistani military strategists (ISI, General Zia's successors) conceived of LeT as a proxy instrument to prosecute Pakistan's claim to Kashmir through 'plausible deniability.' In 1990, Hafiz Saeed formally established LeT as MDI's military wing, initially with ~400 fighters trained in Pakistani Punjab and Afghan Kunar province. Abdullah Azzam (al-Qaeda's ideologue, later killed 1989) provided ideological guidance. Crucially, LeT received direct ISI coordination, training facilities, weapons, and cross-border logistical support from the outset—establishing it as more of a state military proxy than a purely non-state actor.",
